    {
        "user": "U0378MDUG1Y",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1760383105.521499",
        "client_msg_id": "07a11e3d-a0ff-41d1-9f4f-b6b471ce83ba",
        "text": "&gt;  Is coding emancipatory?\n<@UCUSW7WVD> The framing of this question feels off to me because in our current circumstances the answer is inevitably no.  For me, a more useful question is \"_how do we make computing liberatory?_\"\n\n• _computing_ being more broadly concerned with how we use computers than how we program them. For example, for the average person the computer is more of a communication device than a computing device. _coding_ fails to acknowledge this.\n•  _liberatory_ being more of an ideal, future-looking arrangement that inverts these long standing tropes of domination and oppression in computing. While _emancipatory_ is part of that umbrella, it's more about dealing with pressing challenges and identifying strategies that subvert these dynamics. \nI get the sense that our community's explorations in live\/visual\/malleable\/end-user programming implicitly grapple with this question, but I haven't really seen any explicit political stances arise from it. Bhaskar Mitra's work on <http:\/\/arxiv.org\/pdf\/2501.19241v4|Emancipatory Information Retrieval> (also their <https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/watch?v=wK-nHCg_ZHg|talk>) and the <https:\/\/sapphirepunk.com\/|Sapphire Punk Manifesto> are quite inspirational to me, in this respect.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "1092a4f97098",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/avatars.slack-edge.com\/2022-03-23\/3286745266387_1092a4f970985ebc8d2b_72.png",
